,"Acquisition of the 'Blue Series' by Modern Art London.",["Date","2023-01-08T15:04:10.000Z"],"/img/clay-image-1.jpg","exhibitions-sub-page","## The Blue Series\n\nWe are honored to have the entire \"Blue Series\" acquired by Modern Art London for their permanent collection. This series explored the gradients of cobalt oxide in porcelain.\n\nThe pieces will be on display in the West Wing starting next month.","src/content/sold/london-gallery-sale.md","1e2d20557f691182",{"html":280,"metadata":281},"\u003Ch2 id=\"the-blue-series\">The Blue Series\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>We are honored to have the entire “Blue Series” acquired by Modern Art London for their permanent collection. This series explored the gradients of cobalt oxide in porcelain.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>The pieces will be on display in the West Wing starting next month.\u003C/p>",{"headings":282,"localImagePaths":286,"remoteImagePaths":287,"frontmatter":288,"imagePaths":290},[283],{"depth":27,"slug":284,"text":285},"the-blue-series","The Blue Series",[],[],{"templateKey":275,"thumbnail":274,"date":289,"title":271,"description":272},["Date","2023-01-08T15:04:10.000Z"],[],"london-gallery-sale.md","private-collection-nyc",{"id":292,"data":294,"body":299,"filePath":300,"digest":301,"rendered":302,"legacyId":314},{"title":295,"description":296,"date":297,"thumbnail":298,"templateKey":275},"Private Collection, NYC","A curated set of large scale vessels for a private residence.",["Date","2023-01-07T15:04:10.000Z"],"/img/clay-images-8.jpg","## Architectural Scale\n\nThis commission involved creating three large-scale vessels for a minimalist loft in Tribeca. The challenge was to create forms that held their own against the industrial architecture of the space.\n\nThe pieces were coiled built over several weeks and fired in a reduction atmosphere to achieve a dark, metallic finish.","src/content/sold/private-collection-nyc.md","2955f31f9c60922b",{"html":303,"metadata":304},"\u003Ch2 id=\"architectural-scale\">Architectural Scale\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>This commission involved creating three large-scale vessels for a minimalist loft in Tribeca. The challenge was to create forms that held their own against the industrial architecture of the space.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>The pieces were coiled built over several weeks and fired in a reduction atmosphere to achieve a dark, metallic finish.\u003C/p>",{"headings":305,"localImagePaths":309,"remoteImagePaths":310,"frontmatter":311,"imagePaths":313},[306],{"depth":27,"slug":307,"text":308},"architectural-scale","Architectural Scale",[],[],{"templateKey":275,"thumbnail":298,"date":312,"title":295,"description":296},["Date","2023-01-07T15:04:10.000Z"],[],"private-collection-nyc.md","pages",["Map",317,318,348,349,368,369,390,391,405,406,427,428,266,448],"about",{"id":317,"data":319,"body":327,"filePath":328,"digest":329,"rendered":330,"legacyId":347},{"title":320,"description":321,"date":322,"thumbnail":274,"templateKey":323,"featuredimage":274,"number":324,"pagetype":325},"About","About the Artist",["Date","2023-03-02T10:17:05.133Z"],"about-page",1,[326],"main","![Artist at work](/img/clay-images-11.jpg)\n\n## The Hands Behind the Clay\n\nI am a ceramic artist based in the Pacific Northwest, where the rugged coastline and dense forests inspire my work. My journey with clay began over a decade ago, first as a meditative practice and later as a lifelong obsession with form and fire.\n\nI work primarily with stoneware and porcelain, utilizing both wheel-throwing and hand-building techniques. My philosophy is rooted in wabi-sabi—finding beauty in the imperfect, the impermanent, and the incomplete.\n\n![Studio shelves](/img/clay-images-12.jpg)\n\n### Process & Materials\n\nEvery piece is crafted in my home studio. I formulate my own glazes using locally sourced ash and minerals, resulting in surfaces that are unique to my environment. The firing process is a collaboration with the kiln; I can guide the heat, but the flame has the final say.\n\nWhen I am not in the studio, you can find me hiking the trails of the Cascades or scouring the beach for interesting stones and driftwood.\n\n\u003Ca href=\"https://unsplash.com/@tomcrewceramics\" target=\"_blank\">Image credits - Tom Crew\u003C/a>","src/content/pages/about.md","201837bd9d10bcb4",{"html":331,"metadata":332},"\u003Cp>\u003Cimg src=\"/img/clay-images-11.jpg\" alt=\"Artist at work\">\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"the-hands-behind-the-clay\">The Hands Behind the Clay\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>I am a ceramic artist based in the Pacific Northwest, where the rugged coastline and dense forests inspire my work. My journey with clay began over a decade ago, first as a meditative practice and later as a lifelong obsession with form and fire.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>I work primarily with stoneware and porcelain, utilizing both wheel-throwing and hand-building techniques. My philosophy is rooted in wabi-sabi—finding beauty in the imperfect, the impermanent, and the incomplete.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cimg src=\"/img/clay-images-12.jpg\" alt=\"Studio shelves\">\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch3 id=\"process--materials\">Process &#x26; Materials\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Every piece is crafted in my home studio. I formulate my own glazes using locally sourced ash and minerals, resulting in surfaces that are unique to my environment. The firing process is a collaboration with the kiln; I can guide the heat, but the flame has the final say.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>When I am not in the studio, you can find me hiking the trails of the Cascades or scouring the beach for interesting stones and driftwood.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Ca href=\"https://unsplash.com/@tomcrewceramics\" target=\"_blank\">Image credits - Tom Crew\u003C/a>\u003C/p>",{"headings":333,"localImagePaths":341,"remoteImagePaths":342,"frontmatter":343,"imagePaths":346},[334,337],{"depth":27,"slug":335,"text":336},"the-hands-behind-the-clay","The Hands Behind the Clay",{"depth":338,"slug":339,"text":340},3,"process--materials","Process & Materials",[],[],{"templateKey":32